name: Emancipation Proclamation
summary: Juneteenth commemorates the end of slavery in the United States, marked by the Emancipation Proclamation issued on January 1, 1863. While Juneteenth celebrates this historic day, it is important to recognize that the United States has observed over 20 emancipation days. California's Governor Newsom has proclaimed Juneteenth Day of Observance for 2024. The National Park Service and various organizations, including the Chicago Tribune, Houston Chronicle, and United States Army, have shared the Emancipation Proclamation and its significance. IUN commemorated Juneteenth by reading the document, highlighting the efforts of those who fought for equality. Prince William Living and The Atlantic have also explored the history and impact of Juneteenth and the Emancipation Proclamation, emphasizing the ongoing struggle for freedom.
